The minimum exponent of 2 across all four numbers is 0, so the contribution from prime 2 is \(2^0\). ### Prime 3 Analysis: - From \(\text{lcm}(a, b) = 3^2\), \(\text{lcm}(a, c) = 3^3\), and \(\text{lcm}(a, d) = 3^3\), we conclude \(a\) must have \(3^2\). - From \(\text{lcm}(b, c) = 3^3\), \(\text{lcm}(b, d) = 3^3\), and \(\text{lcm}(c, d) = 3^3\), we determine \(b\), \(c\), and \(d\) must have \(3^3\). The minimum exponent of 3 across all four numbers is 2, so the contribution from prime 3 is \(3^1\). ### Prime 5 Analysis: - From \(\text{lcm}(a, b) = 5^3\), \(\text{lcm}(a, c) = 5^3\), and \(\text{lcm}(a, d) = 5^3\), we conclude \(a\) must have \(5^3\). - From \(\text{lcm}(b, c) = 5^2\), \(\text{lcm}(b, d) = 5^2\), and \(\text{lcm}(c, d) = 5^2\), we determine \(b\), \(c\), and \(d\) must have \(5^2\). The minimum exponent of 5 across all four numbers is 0, so the contribution from prime 5 is \(5^0\). ### Conclusion: Combining the minimum exponents for each prime, we get: \[ \text{gcd}(a, b, c, d) = 2^0 \cdot 3^1 \cdot 5^0 = 3 \] Thus, the final answer is \(\boxed{3}\).
